	For a while I have been working on an example that Wolfgang\
suggested last fall, most recently in conjunction with Linda Gruendken and\
Mark Howison, two of the students working with me this summer.  The time\
has come for some serious modeling and unfortunately David Eigen's\
polyhedral software leaves something to be desired when it comes to\
objects in higher dimensional space and/or with a high degree of symmetry.\
	The object of study is a 3-manifold M constructed from 60\
triangular prisms.  It sits naturally in the 4-sphere S4 obtained by\
intersecting the boundary of the 6-dimensional cube dual CD6 spanned by Ei\
and -Ei for i from 1 to 6 with the hyperplane H through the origin\
perpendicular to (1,1,1,1,1,1), where Ei is the vector with 1 in the i\
place and 0 otherwise.  The cells in S4 will be the intersections of H\
with simplexes in CD6 which are the joins of non-empty simplexes in D+ and\
disjoint simplexes in D-, the 5-simplex antipodal to D+.  For example\
there are sixty vertices in S4 of the form (1/2)(Ei-Ej) with i and j\
distinct.  We can denote this vertex by ij'.  We will get 120 edges of the\
form ijk' or ij'k' with i, j, and k distinct.  There are 210 2-cells, of\
three types: ijkl', ijk'l', and ij'k'l', 180 3-cells of the form ijklm'.\
ijkl'm', ijk'l'm', and ij'k'l'm', and 62 4-cells of the form ijklmn',\
